    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="296"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d296">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/28351b</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Foreign Trade Adviser of the Department of State</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_RRF1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Rose</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Commercial Adviser of the British
                        Embassy</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CSRF1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crawford</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 6, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Sir</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CSRF1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Richard</hi>
                    </persName>: In order that there may be no possible misunderstanding which might
                    cause complications in the future, <pb facs="0472" n="214" xml:id="pg_214"/> in
                    regard to the effect of the negotiations and arrangements which are so
                    pleasantly being conducted by us in the matter of facilitating the shipment of
                    goods to and from countries at war with your Government and to neutral countries
                    contiguous thereto, it seems advisable that we should put on record our
                    understanding that these negotiations and arrangements are to be regarded as
                    informal and unofficial and that neither of our Governments is in any way
                    committed thereby.</p>
                <p>Will you therefore be good enough to write me a letter confirming the above
                    statement of our understanding of the matter.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RRF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert F. Rose</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
